{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"219c9517-1842-4ba1-b4ca-a5828859924b","content":"Yes, you'll hit **framework compatibility issues**. Here's the breakdown:\n\n**MSTest v3 dropped support for:**\n- ❌ `netcoreapp3.1` — no longer supported\n- ❌ `net5.0` — no longer supported\n- ✅ `net462` — still supported (.NET Framework ≥ 4.6.2 is fine)\n\nMSTest v3 requires **.NET 6.0+** for the .NET Core side. You'd need to retarget to something like:\n\n```\n<TargetFrameworks>net6.0;net462</TargetFrameworks>\n```\n\n**Other migration notes:**\n1. **Package consolidation** — MSTest v3 offers a single `MSTest` meta-package replacing the separate `MSTest.TestFramework` and `MSTest.TestAdapter` references.\n2. **Behavioral changes** — e.g., `ClassCleanup` timing defaults changed, and some assert APIs were updated.\n\n**Bottom line:** You cannot migrate to MSTest v3 without dropping `netcoreapp3.1` and `net5.0` from your target frameworks. If you still need to test against those runtimes, you'll need to stay on MSTest v2.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"192ba1de-0b68-4e2a-93e6-30870b334667","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is targeting `net5.0`, `net462`, and `netcoreapp3.1`. Let me check what MSTest v3 supports in terms of target frameworks.\n\nMSTest v3 (MSTest 3.x) dropped support for several older frameworks:\n- .NET Framework < 4.6.2 — `net462` is 4.6.2 so that should be fine\n- .NET Core 3.1 — `netcoreapp3.1` was dropped in MSTest v3\n- .NET 5.0 — `net5.0` was also dropped in MSTest v3\n\n\n- MSTest v3 only supports .NET Framework 4.6.2+, .NET 6.0+, and .NET Standard 2.0, so the user will run into compatibility issues with both `net5.0` and `netcoreapp3.1`. Also, v3 consolidated the package structure into a unified `MSTest` meta-package instead of the separate framework and adapter packages from earlier versions.\n\nThe main breaking changes include dropping support for those older TFMs, shifting to the single meta-package as the recommended approach, and some API/behavioral adjustments like ClassCleanup behavior and Assert changes. The TFM incompatibility is really the core blocker here.","outputTokens":685,"requestId":"4C1D:33A80C:295516:307765:6A01423A"},"id":"57a77614-1a4b-4014-af4b-dc90224bd9a8","timestamp":"2026-05-11T02:43:21.032Z","parentId":"12cde5c0-4693-4bf4-9adf-6105345325a4"}
